      "voiceId": "shankara",
      "author": "Śaṅkara",
      "school": "Advaita",
      "work": "Gītā-bhāṣya",
      "locus": "2.57",
      "sanskrit": "yaḥ muniḥ sarvatra deha-jīvitādiṣv api anabhisneho 'bhisneha-varjitas tat tat prāpya śubhāśubhaṃ tat tat śubhaṃ aśubhaṃ vā labdhvā nābhinandati na dveṣṭi śubhaṃ prāpya na tuṣyati na hṛṣyati, aśubhaṃ ca prāpya na dveṣṭi ity arthaḥ | tasya evaṃ harṣa-viṣāda-varjitasya vivekajā prajñā pratiṣṭhitā bhavati",
      "ourRendering": "That sage who, everywhere — even in body, life and the rest — is without affection, devoid of affection, on gaining this or that, good or ill, on obtaining this or that, auspicious or inauspicious, neither rejoices nor reviles — on gaining the auspicious he is not gladdened, does not exult; and on gaining the inauspicious he does not revile — that is the meaning. For such a one, thus devoid of elation and dejection, the prajñā born of discrimination stands firm, coming to be established.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/shankara_gita_bhasya.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/6_sastra/3_phil/vedanta/bhgsbh_u.htm)",
