      "locus": "2.58",
      "sanskrit": "yadā saṃharate samyag upasaṃharate cāyaṃ jñāna-niṣṭhāyāṃ pravṛtto yatiḥ kūrmo 'ṅgāni iva yathā kūrmo bhayāt svāny aṅgāni upasaṃharati sarvaśaḥ sarvataḥ, evaṃ jñāna-niṣṭhaḥ indriyāṇi indriyārthebhyaḥ sarva-viṣayebhya upasaṃharate | tasya prajñā pratiṣṭhitā ity uktārthaṃ vākyam",
      "ourRendering": "When this one — the ascetic engaged in the steadiness of knowledge — draws in fully, that is, withdraws as well, just as a tortoise draws in its limbs: as a tortoise out of fear draws in its own limbs from every side, on all sides, so the one steadfast in knowledge draws in the indriyas from their objects, from all the spheres of sense. ‘His prajñā stands firm’ — the sentence whose meaning has already been stated.",
