      "locus": "2.58",
      "sanskrit": "idānīṃ kim āsīteti praśnasyottaraṃ vaktum ārabhate bhagavān ṣaḍbhiḥ ślokaiḥ | tatra prārabdha-karma-vaśād vyutthānena vikṣiptānīndriyāṇi punar upasaṃhṛtya samādhy-artham eva sthita-prajñasyopaveśanam iti darśayitum āha yadeti | ayaṃ vyutthitaḥ sarvaśaḥ sarvāṇīndriyārthebhyaḥ śabdādibhyaḥ sarvebhyaḥ | caḥ punar-arthe | yadā saṃharate punar upasaṃharati saṅkocayati | tatra dṛṣṭāntaḥ kūrmo 'ṅgānīva | tadā tasya prajñāḥ pratiṣṭhiteti spaṣṭam | pūrva-ślokābhyāṃ vyutthāna-daśāyām api sakala-tāmasa-vṛtty-abhāva uktaḥ | adhunā tu punaḥ samādhy-avasthāyāṃ sakala-vṛtty-abhāva iti viśeṣaḥ ||58||",
      "ourRendering": "Now He begins, in six verses, to give the answer to the question ‘how does he sit’. There, to show that the sthita-prajña’s sitting is precisely for the sake of samādhi — having again drawn in the indriyas that were scattered through the rising-up brought on by commenced karma — He says ‘yadā’. When this risen-up one, from all the sense-objects, sound and the rest, from all of them — ‘ca’ in the sense of ‘again’ — when he draws in, again withdraws, contracts; there the illustration is ‘like a tortoise its limbs’; then his prajñā stands firm — this is clear. By the previous two verses the absence of every tāmasic modification even in the state of rising-up was stated; now, by contrast, in the renewed state of samādhi there is the absence of every modification — this is the distinction.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)",
