      "sanskrit": "nanu nendriyāṇāṃ viṣayeṣv apravṛttir sthita-prajñasya lakṣaṇaṃ bhavitum arhati | jaḍānām āturāṇām upavāsa-parāṇāṃ ca viṣayeṣv pravṛtter aviśeṣāt | tatrāha viṣayā iti | indriyāir viṣayāṇām āharaṇaṃ grahaṇam āhāraḥ | nirāhārasya indriyāir viṣaya-grahaṇam akurvato dehino dehābhimānino 'jñasya rāgo 'bhilāṣas tad-varjaṃ | abhilāṣasya na nivartata ity arthaḥ | yad vā nirāhārasya upavāsa-parasya viṣayāḥ prāyaśo nivartante kṣudhā-santaptasya śabda-sparśādy-apekṣābhāvāt, kintu rasa-varjaṃ rasāpekṣā tu na nivartata ity arthaḥ | śeṣaṃ samānam ||59||",
      "ourRendering": "But surely the non-engagement of the indriyas with objects cannot be the mark of the sthita-prajña, since there is no difference in the non-engagement with objects of the dull, the sick, and those given to fasting. To that He says, with ‘viṣayāḥ’. The taking-in, the grasping, of objects by the indriyas, is ‘āhāra’ (intake). Of the abstinent, who does not perform the grasping of objects by the indriyas, of the embodied one possessed of body-conceit, of the ignorant, rāga, that is, craving — leaving that out; his craving does not turn away, that is the meaning. Or: of the abstinent, one given to fasting, the objects for the most part turn away, since, scorched by hunger, he has no expectation of sound, touch and the rest; but ‘leaving out the rasa’, the expectation of rasa however does not turn away — that is the meaning. The rest is the same.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)",
