      "locus": "2.59",
      "sanskrit": "na caitallakṣaṇaṃ jñānamayatnato'pi bhavatītyāhottaraślokaiḥ| nirāhāratvena viṣayabhogasāmarthyābhāva eva bhavati| itaraviṣayākāṅkṣābhāvo vā| rasākāṅkṣādirna nivartate| sa tvaparokṣajñānādeva nivartata ityāha – viṣayā iti| ‘ indriyāṇi jayantyāśu nirāhāra manīṣiṇaḥ| varjayitvā tu rasanāmāsau rasye tu vardhate ‘ iti vacanādbhāgavate| rasaśabdasyarāgavācitvācca",
      "ourRendering": "He states by the following verses that this mark, knowledge, does not arise even without effort. By abstinence there comes about merely the absence of capacity to enjoy objects, or the absence of craving for the remaining objects; the craving for rasa and the rest does not turn away. That turns away only from direct knowledge — He says this by ‘viṣayāḥ’. As stated in the Bhāgavata, ‘The thoughtful quickly conquer the indriyas by abstinence; but excepting the tongue (taste), in that taste it grows.’ And because the word ‘rasa’ denotes rāga.",
