      "sanskrit": "evaṃ tarhi tatra kaḥ pratīkāra ity ata āha tānīti | tānīndriyāṇi sarvāṇi jñāna-karma-sādhana-bhūtāni saṃyamya vaśīkṛtya yuktaḥ samāhito nigṛhīta-manāḥ sann āsīta nirvāpāras tiṣṭhet | pramāthināṃ kathaṃ sva-vaśīkaraṇam iti cet tatrāha mat-para iti | ahaṃ sarvātmā vāsudeva eva para utkṛṣṭa upādeyo yasya sa mat-para ekānta-mad-bhakta ity arthaḥ | tathā coktam na vāsudeva-bhaktānām aśubhaṃ vidyate kvacit iti | yathā hi loke balavantaṃ rājānam āśritya dasyavo nigṛhyante rājāśrito 'yam iti jñātvā ca svayam eva tad-vaśyā bhavanti tathaiva bhagavantaṃ sarvāntaryāminam āśritya tat-prabhāveṇaiva duṣṭānīndriyāṇi nigrāhyāṇi punaś ca bhagavad-āśrito 'yam iti matvā tāni tad-vaśyāny eva bhavantīti bhāvaḥ | yathā ca bhagavad-bhakter mahā-prabhāvatvaṃ tathā vistareṇāgre vyākhyāsyāmaḥ | indriya-vaśīkāre phalam āha vaśe hīti | spaṣṭam | tad etad vaśīkṛtendriyaḥ sann āsīteti kim āsīteti praśnasyottaram uktaṃ bhavati ||61||",
      "ourRendering": "If it be so, then what is the remedy there? To that He says ‘tāni’. Reining in, bringing under control, all those indriyas, which are the instruments of knowledge and karma, yoked, composed, of restrained manas, let him sit, abide free of activity. — How is the bringing under control of the churning ones to be had? To that He says ‘mat-paraḥ’: I, the Self of all, Vāsudeva alone, am the Supreme, the most excellent, the one to be sought, of him — he is ‘intent on Me’, the one-pointed devotee of Mine, that is the meaning. As stated, ‘For the devotees of Vāsudeva there is never anything inauspicious.’ Just as in the world, robbers, having taken refuge with a strong king, are subdued — and knowing ‘this one is sheltered by the king’ they themselves become subject to him — so too, having taken refuge with the Lord, the inner controller of all, by His very power are the wicked indriyas to be subdued; and again, thinking ‘this one is sheltered by the Lord’, they become subject to him — this is the import. And as for how great the power of devotion to the Lord is, that we will explain at length later. He states the fruit of the indriyas’ mastery by ‘vaśe hi’ — it is clear. Thus, by ‘being one whose indriyas have been brought under control, let him sit’, the answer to the question ‘how does he sit’ comes to be stated.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)",
