      "locus": "2.62-63",
      "sanskrit": "bāhyendriya-saṃyamābhāve doṣam uktvā manaḥ-saṃyamābhāve doṣam āha dhyāyata iti dvābhyām | guṇa-buddhyā viṣayān dhyāyataḥ puṃsaḥ teṣu saṅga āsaktir bhavati | āsaktyā ca teṣu adhikaḥ kāmo bhavati | kāmāc ca kenacit pratihatāt krodho bhavati | kiṃ ca, krodhād iti | krodhāt saṃmohaḥ kāryākārya-vivekābhāvaḥ | tataḥ śāstrācāryopadiṣṭa-smṛter vibhramo vicalanaṃ bhraṃśaḥ | tato buddheś cetanāyā nāśaḥ | vṛkṣādiṣv ivābhibhavaḥ | tataḥ praṇaśyati mṛta-tulyo bhavati ||62-63||",
      "ourRendering": "Having stated the fault in the absence of reining in the outer indriyas, He states the fault in the absence of reining in the manas by ‘dhyāyataḥ’ in two verses. Of a man brooding on the objects with the notion that they are good, toward those saṅga, clinging, arises; and by that clinging a greater kāma toward them comes to be. And from kāma, when thwarted by someone, anger comes to be. Moreover, ‘krodhāt’: from anger delusion arises, the absence of discrimination of what should and should not be done. Thence there arises confusion, a wavering, a lapse of the memory taught by scripture and teacher. Thence the ruin of the understanding, that is, of awareness — an overpowering of it, as in trees and the like. Thence ‘he perishes’, becomes equal to a dead man.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)",
