      "locus": "2.64",
      "sanskrit": "nanv indriyāṇāṃ viṣaya-pravaṇa-svabhāvānāṃ niroddhum aśakyatvād ayaṃ doṣo duṣparihara iti sthita-prajñatvaṃ kathaṃ syāt ? ity āśaṅkyāha rāga-dveṣa iti dvābhyām | rāga-dveṣa-rahitaiḥ vigata-darpair indriyaiḥ viṣayāṃś carann upabhuñjāno 'pi prasādaṃ śāntiṃ prāpnoti | rāga-dveṣa-rāhityam evāha ātmeti | ātmano manasaḥ vaśyair indriyaiḥ vidheyo vaśavartī ātmā mano yasyeti | anenaiva kathaṃ vrajetety asya caturtha-praśnasya svādhīnair indriyair viṣayān gacchatīty uttaram uktaṃ bhavati ||64||",
      "ourRendering": "But surely, since the indriyas, whose nature is to incline toward objects, cannot be checked, this fault is hard to avert — how then can there be sthita-prajña-hood? Anticipating this, He says ‘rāga-dveṣa’ in two verses. By indriyas free of rāga and dveṣa, devoid of arrogance, ranging over objects, enjoying them, he nonetheless attains serenity, peace. The freedom from rāga and dveṣa He states by ‘ātma’: by indriyas under the control of the self, the manas, he whose self, the manas, is governable, subject to him. By this very thing the answer to the fourth question, ‘how does he move’, comes to be stated: ‘he reaches objects with indriyas under his own control.’",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)",
