      "sanskrit": "yā niśā rātriḥ sarva-padārthānām aviveka-karī tamaḥ-svabhāvatvāt sarva-bhūtānāṃ sarveṣāṃ bhūtānām | kiṃ tat paramārtha-tattvaṃ sthita-prajñasya viṣayaḥ | yathā naktaṃ-carāṇām ahar eva sad anyeṣāṃ niśā bhavati, tadvat naktaṃ-cara-sthānīyānām ajñānāṃ sarva-bhūtānāṃ niśeva niśā paramārtha-tattvam, agocaratvād atad-buddhīnām | tasyāṃ paramārtha-tattva-lakṣaṇāyām ajñāna-nidrāyāḥ prabuddho jāgarti saṃyamī saṃyamavān, jitendriyo yogīty arthaḥ | yasyāṃ grāhya-grāhaka-bheda-lakṣaṇāyām avidyā-niśāyāṃ prasuptāny eva bhūtāni jāgrati iti ucyante, yasyāṃ niśāyāṃ prasuptā iva svapna-dṛśaḥ, sā niśā avidyā-rūpatvāt paramārtha-tattvaṃ paśyato muneḥ | ataḥ karmāṇi avidyāvasthāyām eva codyante, na vidyāvasthāyām | vidyāyāṃ hi satyām udite savitari śārvaram iva tamaḥ praṇāśam upagacchati avidyā | prāk vidyotpatteḥ avidyā pramāṇa-buddhyā gṛhyamāṇā kriyā-kāraka-phala-bheda-rūpā satī sarva-karma-hetutvaṃ pratipadyate | na apramāṇa-buddhyā gṛhyamāṇāyāḥ karma-hetutvopapattiḥ, pramāṇa-bhūtena vedena mama coditaṃ kartavyaṃ karma iti hi karmaṇi kartā pravartate, na avidyā-mātram idaṃ sarvaṃ bheda-jātam iti jñānaṃ tasya ātmajñasya sarva-karma-saṃnyāse eva adhikāro na pravṛttau | tathā ca darśayiṣyati --- tad-buddhayas tad-ātmānaḥ ity ādinā jñāna-niṣṭhāyām eva tasya adhikāram | tatrāpi pravartaka-pramāṇābhāve pravṛtty-anupapattiḥ iti cet, na | svātma-viṣayatvād ātma-vijñānasya | na hy ātmanaḥ svātmani pravartaka-pramāṇāpekṣatā, ātmatvād eva | tad-antatvāc ca sarva-pramāṇānāṃ pramāṇatvasya | na hy ātma-svarūpādhigame sati punaḥ pramāṇa-prameya-vyavahāraḥ saṃbhavati | pramātṛtvaṃ hy ātmanaḥ nivartayati antyaṃ pramāṇam | nivartayad eva cāpramāṇībhavati, svapna-kāla-pramāṇam iva prabodhe | loke ca vastv-adhigame pravṛtti-hetutvādarśanāt pramāṇasya | tasmān nātma-vidaḥ karmaṇy adhikāra iti siddham",
      "ourRendering": "What is night for all beings — night, since by its very nature of darkness it makes for non-discrimination of all things — for all beings: what is that? The truth of the highest reality, the sphere of the man of settled wisdom. Just as that which is day to the night-rangers, being verily that, is night to others, so for all beings — the ignorant, who stand in the place of night-rangers — the truth of the highest reality is like night, night, because it is beyond the range of those whose understanding is not turned to it. In that, characterized by the truth of the highest reality, awakened from the sleep of ignorance, the one who reins himself in — possessed of the reining-in, of conquered indriyas, the yogin — keeps watch. And that wherein, in the form of the distinction of grasped and grasper, the night of ignorance, beings are said to be awake while they are verily asleep — wherein they are like sleepers having dream-visions — that is night, because it is of the nature of ignorance, for the sage who sees the truth of the highest reality. Hence works are enjoined only in the state of ignorance, not in the state of knowledge; for when knowledge is present — once it exists, as the nocturnal darkness comes to destruction when the sun has risen — ignorance perishes. Prior to the arising of knowledge, ignorance, grasped by an understanding that treats it as a valid means of knowledge, taking the form of the distinctions of action, agent-factors and result, comes to assume the status of being the cause of all karma; whereas of ignorance grasped by an understanding that treats it as no valid means of knowledge, no such causal status can be established. For the agent sets to work in karma thinking, ‘the karma is enjoined for me as a duty by the Veda, which has become a valid means of knowledge’; but not so the knower of the Self, whose knowledge is, ‘this whole brood of distinction is nothing but ignorance’: of that knower of the Self the authority lies in the renunciation of all karma alone, not in engagement. And so He will show — by the passage beginning ‘those whose understanding is fixed on That, those whose self is That’ — that his authority lies in steadfastness in knowledge alone. ‘But even there, in the absence of an instigating means of knowledge, engagement in action is untenable’ — if one so objects, no: because the cognition of the Self has one’s own Self as its object. For the Self has no dependence on an instigating means of knowledge with regard to its own self, precisely because it is the very Self; and because the validity of all the means of knowledge terminates in That. For once the Self’s own nature is attained, the transaction of means-of-knowledge and object-of-knowledge is no longer possible: the last, final means of knowledge sets aside the knower-hood of the Self, and in the very act of setting it aside becomes a non-means-of-knowledge, like the dream-time means of knowledge on awakening. And in the world too, no causing of further activity is observed of a means of knowledge once the thing is attained. Therefore for the knower of the Self there is no authority in karma — thus it is established.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/shankara_gita_bhasya.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/6_sastra/3_phil/vedanta/bhgsbh_u.htm)",
