      "work": "Gūḍhārtha-dīpikā",
      "locus": "2.69",
      "sanskrit": "tad evaṃ mumukṣuṇā prajñā-sthairyāya prayatna-pūrvakam indriya-saṃyamaḥ kartavya ity uktaṃ sthita-prajñasya tu svataḥ siddha eva sarvendriya-saṃyama ity āha yā niśeti | yā vedānta-vākya-janita-sākṣātkāra-rūpāhaṃ brahmāsmīti prajñā sarva-bhūtānām ajñānāṃ niśeva niśā tān praty aprakāśa-rūpatvāt | tasyāṃ brahma-vidyā-lakṣaṇāyāṃ sarva-bhūta-niśāyāṃ jāgarti ajñāna-nidrāyāḥ prabuddhaḥ san sāvadhāno vartate saṃyamīndriya-saṃyamavān sthita-prajña ity arthaḥ | yasyāṃ tu dvaita-darśana-lakṣaṇāyām avidyā-nidrāyāṃ prasuptāny eva bhūtāni jāgrati svapnavad vyavaharanti sā niśā na prakāśata ātma-tattvaṃ paśyato 'parokṣatayā muneḥ sthita-prajñasya | yāvad dhi na prabudhyate tāvad eva svapna-darśanaṃ bodhya-paryantatvād bhramasya tattva-jñāna-kāle tu na bhrama-nimittaḥ kaścid vyavahāraḥ | tad uktaṃ vārtika-kāraiḥ - kāraka-vyavahāre hi śuddhaṃ vastu na vīkṣyante | śuddhe vastuni siddhe ca kāraka-vyāpṛtis tathā || kākolūka-niśevāyaṃ saṃsāro 'jñātma-vedinoḥ | yā niśā sarva-bhūtānām ity avocat svayaṃ hariḥ || iti | tathā ca yasya viparīta-darśanaṃ tasya na vastu-darśanaṃ viparīta-darśanasya vastv-adarśana-janyatvāt | yasya ca vastu-darśanaṃ tasya na viparīta-darśanaṃ viparīta-darśana-kāraṇasya vastv-adarśanasya vastu-darśanena bādhitatvāt | tathā ca śrutiḥ - yatra vā anyad iva syāt tatrānyo 'nyat paśyet | yatra svasya sarvam ātmaivābhūt tat kena kaṃ paśyet || iti vidyāvidyayor vyavasthām āha | yathā kākasya rātry-andhasya dinam ulūkasya divāndhasya niśā rātrau paśyataś colūkasya yad dinaṃ rātrir eva sā kākasyeti mahad āścaryam etat | atas tattva-darśibhiḥ katham āvidyaka-kriyā-kārakādi-vyavahāraḥ syād iti svataḥ siddha eva tasyendriya-saṃyama ity arthaḥ ||69||",
      "ourRendering": "Thus it was said that the seeker of release should, with effort, effect the reining-in of the indriyas for the firmness of prajñā; but for the sthita-prajña the reining-in of all the indriyas is accomplished of itself — so He says ‘yā niśā’. That prajñā ‘I am Brahman’, of the form of the direct realization born of the Vedānta-sentence, is, for all beings, the ignorant, like night — night, since toward them it is of an unillumined nature. In that night-of-all-beings marked by the knowledge of Brahman, ‘he keeps watch’: awakened from the sleep of ignorance, he abides attentive — the one who reins himself in, possessed of the reining-in of the indriyas, the sthita-prajña, that is the meaning. But that wherein, in the sleep of ignorance marked by the dualistic view, beings, though verily asleep, ‘are awake’ — they carry on their dealings like dreamers — that is night: it does not shine for the sage, the sthita-prajña, who sees, directly, the truth of the Self. For so long as one is not awakened, just so long alone does dream-seeing last, since error reaches only as far as the awakening; but at the time of the knowledge of truth there is no single dealing occasioned by error. That is stated by the author of the Vārtika: ‘in the transaction of agency the pure reality is not beheld; and when the pure reality is established, the busying with agency so too ceases.’ ‘Like crow and owl is this saṃsāra for the ignorant and the knower of the Self; Hari himself declared “what is night for all beings.”’ And so, of him who has the contrary view there is not the seeing of the reality, since the contrary view is born of the non-seeing of the reality; and of him who has the seeing of the reality there is not the contrary view, since the cause of the contrary view, the non-seeing of the reality, is sublated by the seeing of the reality. So too the śruti: ‘Where there is duality as it were, there one sees another; but where, for him, everything has become the very Self, then by what should one see whom?’ — He declares the settled distinction of knowledge and ignorance. Just as for the crow, night-blind, it is day, and for the owl, day-blind, it is night, and to the owl seeing by night, that which is day is, verily, night for the crow — this is a great wonder. Therefore, for the seers of truth, how could there be the ignorance-born transaction of agency and the like? So the reining-in of the indriyas is, for him, accomplished of itself — that is the meaning.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)",
